React Error #310: "Rendered more hooks than during the previous render"
This error occurs when the number of hooks called differs between renders. Here are all possible reasons and solutions:
1. Conditional Hook Calls (Most Common)
Reason: Hooks inside if, for, or ternary operators that may not execute consistently.
Location in your code: Check OrderConfirmationModal, SuccessModal, Cart components
Solution:

Move hooks outside conditionals
Call hooks at the top level, before any conditional logic
Example fix:

javascript// ❌ WRONG
if (isOpen) {
  const [state, setState] = useState('');
}

// ✅ CORRECT
const [state, setState] = useState('');
if (isOpen) {
  // use state here
}

2. Early Returns After Hooks Not Called
Reason: Early return statements that skip subsequent hook calls.
Location: Your SuccessModal and Cart components have early returns
Solution:
javascript// ❌ WRONG - early return skips hooks
if (!isOpen) return null;
const [state, setState] = useState('');

// ✅ CORRECT - call hooks first
const [state, setState] = useState('');
if (!isOpen) return null;

3. Hooks in Nested Functions/Callbacks
Reason: Hooks called inside useEffect, event handlers, or nested functions.
Solution:
javascript// ❌ WRONG
const handleClick = () => {
  const [state, setState] = useState('');
};

// ✅ CORRECT
const [state, setState] = useState('');
const handleClick = () => {
  // use state here
};

4. Conditional Component Rendering Affecting Hook Count
Reason: Parent components conditionally rendering child components with hooks.
Example in your code:
javascript// In NewOrderEntry
if (isMobile && !isModal) {
  return null; // Cart component - this skips hooks
}
Solution: Always render the component, control visibility with CSS/state instead.

5. Multiple useMemo/useCallback Dependencies Changing
Reason: Dependency arrays causing component unmount/remount, changing hook execution.
Solution: Verify dependency arrays are stable and don't include new objects/functions each render.

6. Async Operations Causing Re-renders
